2) ROC curve based on the validation data

Comment on the predictive power of the model based on ROC chart and AUC values.

train_fpr, train_tpr = ROCCurves.roc(train_pred, train_dataset.target)

    ylabel="True Positive Rate (TPR)",
    title ="Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve", linewidth=2, legend=:bottomright)

(4p) A following confusion matrix is given:

A\P 1 0
1 123 321
0 324 456

Prediction values are in columns, actual values in rows.

Calculate:

  • Accuracy
  • Precision
  • Recall
  • F1-score
In [173]:
TP = 123
TN = 456
FP = 321
FN = 324

f1 =  2 * precision * recall / (precision + recall)


accuracy = (TP + TN) / (TP + TN + FP + FN)


precision = TP / (TP + FP)


recall = TP / (TP + FN)


println("Accuracy:", accuracy)
println("Precision:", precision)
println("Recall:", recall)
println("f1:", f1)

Accuracy:0.4730392156862745
Precision:0.27702702702702703
Recall:0.2751677852348993
f1:0.27609427609427606

(3p) Explain shortly how crossvalidation works. Why is it used in Machine Learning workflows? #

(2p) What are the differences between inherent and model independent interpretability algorithms? Give an example of at least two inherently interpretable models. Give an example of at least two model agnostic techniques.

Inherent interpretability algorithms are models that are designed to be inherently interpretable, meaning they provide understandable and transparent explanations of their decisions, such as decision trees and linear regression. Model-agnostic interpretability techniques are independent of the specific model and can be applied to any black-box model. Examples include LIME (Local Interpretable Model-agnostic Explanations) and SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations).

function varimp(df::DataFrame, model, ref_rmse::Float64, reps::Int = 10, random_seed::Int = 1)
    X = df[:, 1:end-1]
    y = df[:, end]
    features = names(X)
    perm_feat_imp = []
    for name in features
        rmse = []
        df_shuffle = copy(X)
        for _ in 1:reps
            Random.seed!(random_seed)
            Random.shuffle!(df_shuffle[!, name])
            if model isa Booster
                prediction = XGBoost.predict(model, Matrix(df_shuffle))
            elseif model isa StatsModels.TableRegressionModel
                prediction = GLM.predict(model, hcat(df_shuffle, y))
            elseif model isa Chain
                prediction = transpose(model(transpose(Matrix(df_shuffle)))) 
            else
                throw(DomainError("Unsupported model"))
            end
            push!(rmse, RMSE(y, prediction))
        end
        rmse = rmse .- ref_rmse
        push!(perm_feat_imp, (feature = name, rmse_change = mean(rmse), rmse_std = std(rmse)))
    end
    return sort!(DataFrame(perm_feat_imp), :rmse_change, rev = true)
end

In [300]:
function predict_function(model, data)
    if model isa Booster
        prediction = StatsModels.predict(model, data)
    elseif model isa StatsModels.TableRegressionModel
        data.medv .= 1
        prediction = GLM.predict(model, data)
    else
        throw(DomainError("Unsupported model"))
    end
    return DataFrame(y = prediction)
end

Other features such as cylinders, acceleration, horsepower, and displacement also have specific effects on the output. The shap_effect_sd accompanying each SHAP value represents the standard deviation of the SHAP effect for the respective feature, indicating the precision of the SHAP effect. Finally, the intercept value is 19.3858. SHAP values are used to understand the contribution of features to the output. Negative values indicate a decrease in the output, while positive values indicate an increase. The magnitude of the SHAP values represents the strength of the feature's impact on the output. SHAP values are a valuable tool for understanding model interpretability and determining the importance ranking of features.
